Mount Hood, Oregon __________________________________________________________________
From: Scott, et.al., 1997, Volcano Hazards in the Mount Hood Region, Oregon: USGS Open-File Report 97-89
Snow-clad Mount Hood dominates the Cascade skyline from the Portland metropolitan area to the wheat fields of Wasco and Sherman Counties.
The mountain contributes valuable water, scenic, and recreational resources that help sustain the agricultural and tourist segments of the economies of surrounding cities and counties.
Mount Hood is also one of the major volcanoes of the Cascade Range, having erupted repeatedly for hundreds of thousands of years, most recently during two episodes in the past 1,500 years.
The last episode ended shortly before the arrival of Lewis and Clark in 1805.
When Mount Hood erupts again, it will severely affect areas on its flanks and far downstream in the major river valleys that head on the volcano.
Volcanic ash may fall on areas up to several hundred kilometers downwind.
Eruptive activity at Mount Hood during the past 30,000 years has been dominated by growth and collapse of lava domes.
The last two episodes of eruptive activity occurred 1,500 and 200 years ago.
Repeated collapse of lava domes extruded near the site of Crater Rock, Mount Hood's youngest lava dome, generated pyroclastic flows and lahars and built much of the broad smooth fan on the south and southwest flank of the volcano.
